<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-26T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-26T15:00:00-05:00" n="595" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d595">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/834a</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-26T16:00:00-04:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">September 26, 1918, 4 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1631. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from War Trade Board]:</p>
                            <p>No. 1285. We have declined to accede to the request of the Dutch
                                Chargé that the Dutch S.S. <hi rend="italic">Frisia</hi>, which is
                                now about to sail from Argentina for Holland via New York, be
                                permitted to load in the United States an additional cargo of grain,
                                representing the difference between the quantity of coal to be
                                consumed upon her trip from Buenos Aires to New York and the
                                quantity required for her trip from New York to Holland, some 500
                                tons. You will recall that we permitted this some time ago in the
                                case of the S.S. <hi rend="italic">Hollandia</hi>. We are now of the
                                opinion that no further exportation of foodstuffs should be
                                permitted to be made from the United States to Holland until the
                                conclusion of some more satisfactory arrangement with that
                                country.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>